            <lb/>
Is the melancholy and debility produced<lb/>
by sickness favourable to intellectual<lb/>
exertion? I believe so. The mind necessarily<lb/>
becomes contemplative when the body is no<lb/>
longer active, and the empire of sensation<lb/>
yields to that of imagination. Under such<lb/>
circumstances, likewise, the mind is sober<lb/>
and disposed to discover realities, and values<lb/>
quiet and comfort, more than pomp and<lb/>
eclat. During the last fortnight I have seen<lb/>
and felt some novelties; yet but for the<lb/>
wretched state of body in which I am,<lb/>
they probably would never have been<lb/>
committed to paper.<lb/>
I left <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag259"
                ref="#place_071"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag259" type="place">
          London
        </name>
            </rs> on the 30<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">th</hi> of June, Lady M.<lb/>
would say "on the wings of hope aided by<lb/>
the paddles of steam" I had never before<lb/>
seen the whole of the river, or known the<lb/>
immensity of British capital industry and<lb/>
activity displayed by the great inlet to<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="42"
                xml:id="pb-42"
                facs="#i42"/>
            <lb/>
the most wonderful city in the world.<lb/>
We left <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag260"
                ref="#place_1088"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag260" type="place">
          Greenwich
        </name>
            </rs> at 2 O Clock, and before<lb/>
nine we were coasting the Suffolk low<lb/>
lands, and lost sight of land before it<lb/>
was dark. A favourable wind and<lb/>
steam enabled us to see the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag261"
                ref="#place_1090"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag261" type="place">
          coast of<lb/>Holland
        </name>
            </rs> next day at three, and before<lb/>
