consider the motion and action of a<lb/>
Steam Engine as produced by the solid<lb/>
matter; ignorant of the elements of fire<lb/>
and water which are the immediate cause<lb/>
of its activity, or of the physical discovery<lb/>
of human intelligence by which the<lb/>
combinations producing it were made.<lb/>
What is the instinct of animals, but<lb/>
an immediate revelation, and they have<lb/>
more instinct in proportion as they have<lb/>
less reason. In the infancy of human<lb/>
society, man being a more perfect<lb/>
animal required <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">moral instincts</hi>, or<lb/>
revelations, to preserve his social existence<lb/>
Now even the rudest people are<lb/>
accessible to the more civilized, and<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="126"
                xml:id="pb-126"
                facs="#i126"/>
            <lb/>
special revelations are no longer necessary<lb/>
It is quite certain, that in these revelations,<lb/>
no new ideas were given, and no new<lb/>
impressions received, even the supposed<lb/>
presence of Deity was an imagination<lb/>
of a human form, and the miracles<lb/>
mere delusions of the human mind,<lb/>
though clearly disposed to these delusions<lb/>
by the existence of the instinct, and<lb/>
this indeed is in accordance with<lb/>
the Divine wisdom and power, as it<lb/>
is much more easy for mind to produce<lb/>
an ideal conviction of satisfied appetite<lb/>
than to create a new quantity of matter,<lb/>
which must have been the case if<lb/>
sufficient to satisfy the multitude<lb/>
in the wilderness had been produced<lb/>
from the small loaves and fishes.<lb/>
            <milestone xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                       unit="section"
                       rend="line"/>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="127"
                xml:id="pb-127"
                facs="#i127"/>
            <lb/>
123<lb/>
If we suppose very high pressure,<lb/>
even organic compounds may exist<lb/>
under circumstances which would<lb/>
appear incompatible with them<lb/>
If we suppose an <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag642"
                ref="#chemical_503"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag642">
          aqueous vapour
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
atmosphere swimming above our common<lb/>
atmosphere, <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">and</del> weighing 1000 times<lb/>
as much, and our atmosphere heated<lb/>
so highly that the pressure made it<lb/>
exactly of the same specific gravity as<lb/>
it now is; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag643"
                ref="#chemical_090"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag643">
          Limestone
          
        </term>
            </rs> might be fluid,<lb/>
and yet animals live in water, because<lb/>
their decomposition would not be more<lb/>
certain than it now is; and there<lb/>
would be very little difference in the<lb/>
surface, except in the fluidity of certain<lb/>
forms of matter, and the extensive<lb/>
atmosphere and the self shining character<lb/>
of the Globe. The force of attraction<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="128"
                xml:id="pb-128"
                facs="#i128"/>
            <lb/>
being so great in the Sun, no decomposition<lb/>
or changes could take place if there<lb/>
was not some compensating rotative<lb/>
energy; so that if it be composed of<lb/>
matter like our earth, <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">life</hi> could<lb/>
not exist upon it unless its temperatures<lb/>
were very elevated. The planets<lb/>
most distant from the Sun are <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">by</del>
            <lb/>
larger, but composed of lighter matter<lb/>
probably: for the same reason, it<lb/>
may be a matter more susceptible<lb/>
of expansion from heat.<lb/>
But if C. is a reptile, why not<lb/>
destroy him? Reptiles are vivacious<lb/>
and being cold blooded have great<lb/>
powers of endurance and life. Reptiles<lb/>
often gain elevations which noble<lb/>
beings can never reach; but it is<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="129"
                xml:id="pb-129"
                facs="#i129"/>
            <lb/>
125<lb/>
by crawling and creeping: a lizard<lb/>
in crawling up a column takes the<lb/>
dirtiest path because it is the easiest.<lb/>
It is now 11 years since I have<lb/>
written any thing in this book. I<lb/>
take it again Feby. 17. 1821. I have<lb/>
gained much since that period, and<lb/>
I have lost something; yet I am<lb/>
thankful to Infinite Wisdom for blessings<lb/>
and benefits, and I bow with reverence<lb/>
beneath his Chastisements, which have<lb/>
been always in mercy. May every<lb/>
year make<del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">s</del> me better, more useful, less<lb/>
selfish, and more devoted to the cause<lb/>
of humanity and Science. When I<lb/>
reflect upon this world, I cannot help<lb/>
sometimes entertaining the idea as<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="130"
                xml:id="pb-130"
                facs="#i130"/>
            <lb/>
if man were but the sport of some<lb/>
loftier intelligence, and as if he were<lb/>
produced rather to shew the power and<lb/>
benevolence, than the perfect wisdom<lb/>
of the Divine Mind; a sort of creative<lb/>
sport of Divine energy. For in all<lb/>
the other productions belonging to the<lb/>
globe, there are fixed and simple laws<lb/>
which always produce their results uniformly<lb/>
and according to an invariable order<lb/>
But reason, which is considered as the<lb/>
highest gift of heaven, and <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">his</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">the</add> passion,<lb/>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">of men</add> lead to results the most extraordinary<lb/>
and unexpected. Man is made<lb/>
without clothing, and no sooner has<lb/>
he discovered means of defending<lb/>
himself from the external elements, <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">as you have observed</add>
            <lb/>
than he instantly creates useless forms<lb/>
and finery, and tortures his organs<lb/>
into the most uncouth shapes to<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="131"
                xml:id="pb-131"
                facs="#i131"/>
            <lb/>
127<lb/>
gratify certain capricious ideas of<lb/>
fashion or beauty.<lb/>
The first display of reason in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag644"
                ref="#place_1136"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag644" type="place">
          new<lb/>South Wales
        </name>
            </rs> is, that the Savage extracts<lb/>
one of his fine teeth. In another<lb/>
country, the whole skin is cut and<lb/>
pickled. In <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag645"
                ref="#place_019"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag645" type="place">
          China
        </name>
            </rs> the women squeeze<lb/>
their feet into shoes, and torture themselves<lb/>
more than if they went barefooted;<lb/>
and in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag646"
                ref="#place_121"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag646" type="place">
          England
        </name>
            </rs> men compress themselves<lb/>
in stays: Painting the skin with<lb/>
noxious substances is another effort<lb/>
of reason. Beasts fight, animated<lb/>
by the passion of love, and the strongest<lb/>
perpetuates the species. Men fight and<lb/>
destroy each other without being animated<lb/>
by any passion at all; but because<lb/>
persons whom they support by their<lb/>
labour, and who never do any thing<lb/>
in return, quarrel about some spot<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="132"
                xml:id="pb-132"
                facs="#i132"/>
            <lb/>
of land, or some river or some desert,<lb/>
which is of no importance whatever<lb/>
to the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">inhab</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">comb</add>atants.<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Reason induces men to build houses</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">for shelter, but their great expences</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
