            <lb/>
1<lb/>
Religion. - Instinct.<lb/>
With respect to my ideas of revelation<lb/>
and instinct; - it is as easy for the Supreme<lb/>
Intelligence to form a thinking being<lb/>
such as a <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag665"
                ref="#person_036"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag665" type="person">
          Newton
        </name>
            </rs>, as a chrystal,<lb/>
without the slow process of generation<lb/>
of body or mind.<lb/>
[short horizontal rule]<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag666"
                ref="#misc_580"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag666">
          Adams
        </term>
            </rs> first inspiration transmitted<lb/>
to his offspring.<lb/>
Religious instincts may be hereditary;<lb/>
Moral excellencies and physical as well<lb/>
as defects or diseases.<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag667"
                ref="#misc_731"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag667">
          Levites
        </term>
            </rs>. Jews. Dogs.<lb/>
The <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">quality</hi>, disease or virtue of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
